Single Cell Sequencing Analysis

dependancies

library('Seurat')
library('tidyverse')
library('devtools')
library('SeuratData')

Data Download

installing Seurat data set from publicly available source (Satija Lab)

InstallData('pbmc3k')
data('pbmc3k')

Quality Control

  1. find the proportion of mitochondrial RNA within a sample -> dying cells express higher relative mitochondrial RNA -> as such dying cells can be eliminated based on there MT RNA expression

  2. plot a histogram of MT RNA to ensure normal Guassian distribution

  3. plot a histogram of n_countRNA ensure normal Guassian distribution -> ensure there are not a lot of samples have low expression

pbmc3k$percent.mito <- PercentageFeatureSet(pbmc3k, '^MT-')
hist(pbmc3k$percent.mito, breaks = 100)

hist(pbmc3k$nCount_RNA, breaks = 100)

filtering & normalization

  1. remove cells with high mitochondrial RNA -> based on histogram above: visually 5+ is excessive

  2. NormalizeData is simply a log transformation

pbmc3k <- NormalizeData(pbmc3k)

Performing log-normalization

PCA analysis

  1. in order to have equally weighted genes in PCA analysis they need to be normalized and zero centered (z-score)

  2. run PCA analysis -> PC-1 is the line which provides the largest SD between the data

  3. Elbow plot -> showing the standard deviation for each PC

  4. Dim Plot -> regular PCA plot without highlighting a feature

  5. Feature Plot -> PCA plot with a featuer of interest highlighted -> ex. perhaps you want to know the T-cell population

pbmc3k <- ScaleData(pbmc3k)
Centering and scaling data matrix

non-linear dimensional reduction

UMAP is considered better than t-SNE but feel free to utilize either: -> here I use UMAP

  1. UMAP -> find the elbow on elbow plot (in our case this is around 10) -> take just those 10 dimensions and reduce them into 2D space

  2. DimPlot -> simply plot the UMAP on a scatter plot

  3. FeaturePlot -> simply plot the UMAP on a scatter plot with features

pbmc3k <- RunUMAP(pbmc3k, dims=1:10)

Clustering

  1. findNeighbours -> uses PCA plot to find Neighbours in the graph

  2. FindClusters -> assigns clusters based on the resolutaion metric

  3. findMarkers -> find the markers that define a cluster -> you can then use a FeaturePlot to highlight
